China Stocks: Anhui Conch, Chaori Solar, Dongfang Electric, SAIC

-- B y   B l o o m b e r g   N e w s
-- 
2011-09-21T07:41:16Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-20/anhui-conch-saic-sany-heavy-industry-china-stock-preview.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in China trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses as of 3 p.m. close.  The Shanghai Composite Index, which tracks the bigger of
China’s stock exchanges, rose 65.21 points, or 2.7 percent, to
2,512.96, its biggest advance since Aug. 25. The  CSI 300 Index (SHSZ300) 
gained 3 percent to 2,771.01.  Nuclear power equipment-related stocks: Nanfang Ventilator
Co. (300004 CH), a manufacturer of ventilators for nuclear power
stations, added 3.2 percent to 30.80 yuan. Dongfang Electric
Corp. (600875 CH), China’s second-biggest maker of power
equipment, jumped 7.1 percent to 23.05 yuan, the biggest gain
since Jan. 27. China First Heavy Industries Co. (601106 CH), a
maker of equipment used in the mining and energy industries,
surged the 10 percent daily limit to 3.98 yuan.  China may resume approvals for new nuclear power projects
early next year, China Securities Journal reported, citing
unidentified people.  Anhui Conch Cement Co. (600585 CH), the nation’s largest
cement producer, rose 6.6 percent to 18.54 yuan, the biggest
gain since June 14. Anhui Conch Building Materials Design
Center, an affiliate, purchased 3.2 million shares.  Jiangsu Xiuqiang Glasswork Co. (300160 CH) jumped 7.7
percent to 30.52 yuan, its biggest gain since listing in
January. Profit for the first nine months may jump as much as 81
percent from a year earlier to as much as 92 million yuan ($14.4
million), the company said in a statement yesterday. Third-
quarter profit may rise between 31 percent and 41 percent, it
said.  SAIC Motor Corp. (600104 CH),  China ’s biggest domestic
automaker, gained 5.3 percent to 16.47 yuan. SAIC will develop
electric cars with General Motors Co. to meet Beijing’s demands
for more low-emission vehicles, the two companies said in a
statement yesterday.  Sany Heavy Industry Co. (600031 CH), the biggest Chinese
machinery maker, advanced 4.9 percent to 15.79 yuan. Sany said a
wholly owned unit has signed a contract worth $14.95 million
with Regency Material Trading for machinery sales.  Shanghai Chaori Solar Energy Science & Technology Co.
(002506 CH), a Chinese maker of solar cells, climbed 5.1 percent
to 18.88 yuan. The company said its board of directors approved
a plan to invest 40.8 million euros ($56 million) to set up a
venture with China Solar GmbH.  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Darren Boey at 
 dboey@bloomberg.net  